{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01MEWXyoCGsGTiXijmaMmkzd","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a good picture of the current configuration. Let me summarize what's non-default:\n\n**Non-default vhosts:**\n- `/app` (non-default)\n- `/ops` (non-default)\n\n**Non-default users:**\n- `admin` with `administrator` tag\n- `app-user` with `management` tag\n- `ops-user` with `management` tag\n\n(Default RabbitMQ only has `guest` user)\n\n**Non-default permissions:**\n- `/app`: admin (.*,.*,.*), app-user (.*,.*,.*)\n- `/ops`: admin (.*,.*,.*), ops-user (.*,.*,.*)\n- `/`: admin (.*,.*,.*)\n\n**Non-default policies:**\n- `/app`: ha-all policy with ha-mode=all, ha-sync-mode=automatic\n\n**Non-default queues:**\n- `/app`: app-queue (classic, durable)\n- `/ops`: ops-queue (classic, durable)\n\nSo comparing against the default RabbitMQ state—which has just the `/` vhost, `guest` user, and no policies or custom queues—I can see this setup has been customized with multiple vhosts, users with specific roles, and high-availability configuration on the app vhost.\n\nFor the rollback script, I need to reverse these changes: remove the `ha-all` policy, delete the custom queues, remove the non-default users, and drop the `/app` and `/ops` vhosts. I also notice the `guest` user isn't in the current user list, so it was likely deleted during setup—the rollback should restore it since that's part of the default state.\n\nWriting the rollback script... Finishing the permissions setup and then removing the non-default vhosts to complete the rollback. I'm thinking through the order of operations here—deleting users before vhosts is safe, though I need to be mindful that terminating user connections could impact running applications. The goal is to restore RabbitMQ to its defaults: the `/` vhost with only the `guest` user who has administrator privileges. I'm reconsidering the rollback sequence to make it explicit and reviewable, even though vhost deletion would cascade everything. I'll write a clean, well-commented script that removes policies first, then non-default queues, followed by users and vhosts in a logical order. Delete the /app and /ops vhosts to cascade their associated queues, exchanges, bindings, and permissions, then remove the admin, app-user, and ops-user accounts, and finally restore the guest user with administrator privileges on the default vhost.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":434,"cache_read_input_tokens":33061,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":434},"output_tokens":11,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f7b0dae4-dd1f-41a4-b0d2-cbbf9b9d9efd","uuid":"9c193284-5369-4d30-baac-4304ddd7cf52","request_id":"req_011CcMUF1GwhBRpjYUSuWMDo"}
